Diesel pollution is a serious threat to Oregonians' health and also contributes to climate change. 

Diesel-fueled engines emit more than 40 air toxics, including a number of carcinogens. Diesel exhaust contributes to asthma, cancer, chronic respiratory illnesses and more. For example, a very recent study published in Environmental Health Perspectives found that diesel exhaust is responsible for at least 6% of lung cancer cases in the United States and United Kingdom. Exposure to diesel exhaust is widespread in Oregon, with diesel particulate matter exceeding health benchmarks in 17 counties, home to 87% of the stateâ€™s population.  

While it's troubling that less and less federal (and no state) funding is available to tackle Oregon's diesel problem, this rulemaking will, at the very least, enable the state to take advantage of any federal funds that are available.

We urge EQC to adopt the proposed rules. 

P.S. This lack of funding for diesel clean-up efforts makes it even more essential to move forward with DEQ's Clean Fuels Program. The Clean Fuels Program will result in development and deployment of cleaner alternative fuels, reducing the stateâ€™s long dependence on polluting gasoline and diesel.
